6–1336","1288–1328":"1288–1328","30 March 1336":"30 March 1336","15 July 1410":"15 July 1410","1351":"1351","1 April 1359":"1 April 1359","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","13 June 1360":"13 June 1360","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1359":"1359","1336":"1336","1 January 1327":"1 January 1327","1334":"1334","1410":"1410","1288":"1288","1276":"1276","16 July 1410":"16 July 1410","10 September 1328":"10 September 1328","1328":"1328","Torun, Prussia, Europe":"Thorn, Thorn, West Prussia, Prussia, Germany","Tannenberg, Osterode, East Prussia, Prussia":"Tannenberg, Osterode, East Prussia, Prussia","Grunwald, Poznań, Wielkopolskie, Poland":"Grunwald, Poznań, Greater Poland, Poland","Toruń, Kuyavia-Pomerania, Poland":"Toruń, Kuyavia-Pomerania, Poland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Torun","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hanoch, Moshe, Shira.","Dutch (also <b>Van Toren</b>): topographic name from Middle Dutch <i>tor(r)en</i> ‘tower’ (from Latin <i>turris</i>), or a habitational name from any of many places called with this word.","Swedish (<b>Torén</b>): ornamental name from the personal name <i>Tor(e)</i> (see   Thor  ) + the adjectival suffix <i>-én</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>-enius</i> ‘relating to’."],"variants":[{"name":"Thor","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Erland, Eyvind, Nels.  Southeast Asian Chor, Tong, Chia, Chu, Kong, Seng, Tou, Chee, Ching, Chou, Chue, Eng, Thai, Moua, Neng, Pao, Yeng, Yer, Blong, Chong, Choua, Houa, Shoua, Soua.","Swedish and Danish: from a short form of any of various Scandinavian personal names containing the first element <i>Thor</i> (Old Norse <i>Thórr</i>), the name of the god of thunder in Scandinavian mythology.","English: from the Anglo-Scandinavian name <i>Thōr</i>, <i>Thūr</i>, probably short forms of Old Norse compound names in <i>Thór-</i>, <i>Thúr-</i> (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Nicolaus","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1352627,"age":55,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"description":"The Jagiellonian Dynasty.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicolaus Torun was born on 1 January 1327, in Toruń, Kuyavia-Pomerania, Poland, his father, Sir Nicholaus Torun, was 50 and his mother, Ursula Saxon, was 38. He married Lady Christine Prussian in 1351, in Toruń, Kuyavia-Pomerania, Poland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 15 July 1410, in Grunwald, Poznań, Greater Poland, Poland, at the age of 83, and was buried in Grunwald, Poznań, Greater Poland, Poland."},"et":{"1 January 1327–15 July 1410":"1. jaanuar 1327–15. juuli 1410","1327–1410":"1327–1410","1334–1360":"1334–1360","1359–1410":"1359–1410","1276–1336":"1276–1336","1288–1328":"1288–1328","30 March 1336":"30. märts 1336","15 July 1410":"15. juuli 1410","1351":"1351","1 April 1359":"1. aprill 1359","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","13 June 1360":"13. juuni 1360","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1359":"13